==English==

===Etymology===
A loan word from {{G.}}, possibly a neologism in the German-language Wikipedia.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{wjargon}} A deliberately fictitious entry in an encyclopedia or dictionary, which is intended to be more or less quickly recognized as false by the reader. If expected to be easily identified it might be called an [[Easter egg]] in English (from computer games: a hidden surprise). Subtly hidden ones might be a method of [[branding]] the [[intellectual property]] so it can be recognized if copied.
#*'''2005:''' Eve Maler, ''Pushing String (blog) May 1, 2005'' permalinked at [http://www.xmlgrrl.com/blog/archives/2005/05/01/the-language-log/]:
#*:The post never does find the word it’s looking for, but it eventually alights on a discussion of the Nihilartikel, a fake dictionary or encyclopedia entry created for playful or copyright-trap reasons.
#*'''2005:''' Justin Mason, ''jm's items tagged nihilartikel: Wired Journal Watch: Mountweazel'', at[http://del.icio.us/jm/nihilartikel/]:
#*:Another form of the nihilartikel, or plagiarism-detection honeytoken -- to honour 'Lillian Virginia Mountweazel'.
#*'''2006:''' Anonymous author of ''Blogjam'' blog, ''Pancreas'' archived at [http://www.blogjam.com/2006/07/11/pancreas/]:
#*:The word for ‘deliberate error introduced into a text or map, often for copyright protection reasons’ is ‘nihilartikel’. Or is it?